# Backend-Ready Contracts

Design every module and component as if the backend already exists. The data source can change at any time — mock today, real API tomorrow. Modules and components MUST NEVER know or care where data comes from.

## The Golden Rule

**If a value will come from an API in production, it MUST come through a typed contract (props, context, or service hook). NEVER hardcode it.**

## What is Domain Data

Any value that would come from an API, database, or user session:

- User info (name, avatar URL, email, role)
- Navigation items, menu options, sidebar links
- Lists of entities (channels, messages, projects, teams)
- Feature flags, user preferences, org-level config
- Counts, stats, metadata
- ANY dynamic content that varies per user, session, or deployment

## What is NOT Domain Data

Static, deterministic values that never change per user:

- i18n keys (`tCommon('actions.save')` — static, locale-driven)
- Layout structure (template slots, grid definitions)
- Math/regex constants (`const MAX_RETRIES = 3`)
- Component-internal icons (a close button's X icon)

## Contract = Interface

The contract is the TypeScript interface. It defines what the consumer needs, not where it comes from.

```typescript
// Shell.types.ts — the contract
export interface ShellProps {
  readonly railItems: readonly RailItemConfig[]
  readonly avatarSrc: string
  readonly avatarAlt: string
  readonly children: ReactNode
}
```

## Module Consumes the Contract

The module receives everything via props. It NEVER imports data, fetches data, or defines constants that represent domain state.

```tsx
// GOOD — module knows nothing about data source
export const Shell = ({ railItems, avatarSrc, avatarAlt, children }: ShellProps) => (
  <WorkspaceLayout rail={<Rail items={railItems} avatarSrc={avatarSrc} avatarAlt={avatarAlt} />}>
    {children}
  </WorkspaceLayout>
)

// BAD — module defines its own data
const NAV_ITEMS = [{ label: 'Home', path: '/' }]
const AVATAR = 'https://example.com/avatar.png'

export const Shell = ({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) => (
  <WorkspaceLayout rail={<Rail items={NAV_ITEMS} avatarSrc={AVATAR} />}>
    {children}
  </WorkspaceLayout>
)
```

## Composition Root Provides the Data

The route file (composition root) is the ONLY place where data sources are wired. Today it can be a mock constant. Tomorrow it can be a service hook. The module never changes.

```tsx
// routes/_shell.tsx — composition root

// TODAY: mock data (no backend yet)
const RAIL_ITEMS: readonly RailItemConfig[] = [
  { icon: HomeIcon, labelKey: 'rail.items.home', path: '/' },
]
const MOCK_AVATAR_SRC = 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/0?v=4'

function ShellLayout() {
  return (
    <Shell railItems={RAIL_ITEMS} avatarSrc={MOCK_AVATAR_SRC} avatarAlt="...">
      <Outlet />
    </Shell>
  )
}

// TOMORROW: real service hook (backend exists)
function ShellLayout() {
  const { data: navItems } = useGetNavItems()
  const { data: user } = useGetCurrentUser()

  return (
    <Shell railItems={navItems} avatarSrc={user.avatarUrl} avatarAlt={user.name}>
      <Outlet />
    </Shell>
  )
}
```

## The Swap Test

Ask yourself: **"Can I swap from mock to real API by ONLY changing the composition root?"**

- If YES: the contract is correct.
- If NO: you have hardcoded domain data somewhere. Fix it.

## Rules

- NEVER define domain data (arrays, URLs, user info, config) inside a module or component file
- Modules receive ALL domain data via props — defined in `<Module>.types.ts`
- Components receive ALL domain data via props — defined in `<Component>.types.ts`
- The composition root (route file, provider wrapper) is the ONLY place that decides WHERE data comes from
- Swapping from mock to real service MUST require ZERO changes in modules and components
- Service types from `services/` define the contract — props types reference or extend them
- When creating a new module, always ask: "What data will this need from a backend?" — those are your props
